arities of the South Asian case, the authors theorize what they call "the art of bossing," providing nuanced ideas about crime, corruption, and the lure of the strongman across the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCriminalszSouth AsiavBiography. 0aOrganized crimexPolitical aspectszSouth Asia. 0aPolitical corruptionzSouth Asia. 0aPolitical culturezSouth Asia. 0aPoliticianszSouth AsiavBiography. 4abossism. 4ademocracy. 4aleadership and authority. 4amafias. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aHoque, Ashraf, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMartin, Nicolas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRollier, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRuud, Arild E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStill, Clarinda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360732340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607323.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles